Bill Pinkerton called for equipment on his way to Lower California.

Sunday, February 9, 1947

Worked a little on vegetable cures for snake bite, but put in most of the day packing groceries for European correspondents.

Phil went over the Tia Juana - Mexicali road.
l. Oreganus M DOR 13 mi E of Tia Juana Brush-fields
2. Trimorphodon M DOR Cuesta Alducin (= 3mi E of Alaska or
Alaska Chiquita)

Saturday, February 22, 1947

Worked all day and evening on the snake-bite part of the Indian section. Pretty well exhausted by evening.

Shaw's Trip today
1 Gopher S DOR La Honda Spr. Saved Lt Brush.
1 Banded King M DOR 5 mi. W. Dulzura Cult. fields had eaten small gopher
1 Banded King S DOR Dulzura Trees & light brush.
1 Gopher S. DOR Dulzura Trees & stream
1 Garter M DOR Potrero Brush & rocks.

Sunday, February 23, 1947

Worked all day on the Indian treatment of snake bite; it is now finished down to shamanism - - the last item under Indians remaining unfinished.

Out to dinner tonight.

Sunday, March 16, 1947

Still working on shamanism today, a very slowly going and dreary section. Anyhow made some headway by sticking to it all day and evening with some interruptions.

Ruthling called this noon with his wife and 2 small daughters.

Friday, March 21, 1947

Today started at 2 PM for Los Angeles; a cool day with a few sprinkles of rain. Got there a little after 5. Spent a couple of hours at the Library and cleared up a few items.

Page Edit History:
  • Will 09/07/2012 12:22 PM

Saturday, March 22, 1947 '

Page Edit History:
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:53 PM

Sunday, March 23, 1947

Today started out at 8. Drove around Joshua Tree Nat Monument with the Custodian Frank R. Givens. Clear but rather cool. Went to Keys View again then south via Pinto Basin then South to the highway near Shaver's Summit.

Only reptile seen today = a whiptail at Cottonwood Spring, Riv Co (NW of Shavers Summit.

Drove home via Shaver's Well, Mecca, Brawley, El Centro, and highway 80 arriving at 6:45. Expected to stay at Jacumba, but couldn't find a suitable place.

Miles today 305

Saturday, March 29, 1947

Spent the morning on miscellaneous work, especially incorporating Schmidt's suggestions in Section 4B.

Afternoon on shamanistic treatment of snake bite.

Evening at an Arau concert.

Dr. Tinkham of University of Arizona called today. Had some interesting horned toad specimens from Lower California.

Sunday, March 30, 1947

Finally finished the Indian Section 4A after many months. Still some pick up and cleaning up to do. A very long job it has proved to be.

Saturday, April 5, 1947

Miscellaneous work all day clearing the items that have gathered up while finishing up the Indian section. Worked on the copperhead nomenclature paper; also the gopher snake paper was worked on for page proofs. Was out for dinner.

Dr. Ernest R. Tinkham of Tuscon spent much of the afternoon in the basement working on horned toads. Took quite a bit of my time. Shaw was also there.

Page Edit History:
  • Will 09/07/2012 01:00 PM
  • Will 09/07/2012 12:56 PM
  • pamg 09/01/2012 01:03 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:53 PM

Sunday, April 6, 1947

Finally cleared up all miscellaneous items. Now ready to go back to the food section that I dropped to finish the rewriting of the Indian section last Oct. 6th. Took six months to do a job I thought would take one.

Saturday, April 12, 1947

Not feeling too spry today a/c of some tests by the doctor yesterday.

Dr. Haas of Hebrew University Jerusalem, with his sister-in-law called in the morning. Discussed his herpetological work and the great similarity of Palestine to Southern California, especially our east-west cross section.

Went to a meeting of the zoo directors at noon.

Out to dinner tonight.

Saturday, April 19, 1947

Spent part of the morning on the page proof of the western gopher snake paper.

The afternoon was taken up with arranging the material for the Food Section of the Rattlesnake Paper.

Scholia Club in the evening.

110th

Spent the day arranging data of the food section, except for a couple of hours interviewing Perkins on experiences with feeding at the Zoo. Now have all the data necessary to proceed.

Wednesday, April 23, 1947

Started for the Mojave Desert with C B Perkins. Went out via San Fernando (where we secured auto-court rooms) and Mint Canyon. Made the loop Mojave - Kramer Juct - Adelanto, Palmdale.

Started at 1:20

Reached Mojave at 7:35 cold and windy. New moon 64 degrees F.

1 King Snake S. DOR 6 mi. W. of Boron Kramer Juct 8:40 58 degrees Windy and cold.

Back at San Fernando at 11:10 383 miles today.

Evening drive (high speed most of the time) 2 hrs. 85 miles

Thursday, May 8, 1947

Today I went out to see the New Descanso 66 KV line. Went out via Spring Valley, Jamacha, Dehesa, Alpine Junction, and back via 80. A cool cloudy day 9:30-11:30 AM. 52 miles.

1 Boyles King L DOR Jamacha grass
1 Red racer L LOR Dehesa Lite brush
1 Gopher M DOR Dehesa brush
1 Gopher L COR Dehesa brush (very large about 4.5 ft. turned him loose.)

Allan K left a Boyles King L and a med gopher picked up at Flinn Spring. The king started to eat the gopher in the sack.

Friday, May 9, 1947

Shaws Sonora trip (May 12, continued)

1 Callisaurus DOR 5.5 mi. SW of El Papalote sandy desert, creosote bush
1 Uma n. cowlesi DOR 5 mi. SW of El Papalote creosote bush
1 Callisaurus DOR 3.5 mi. NE of El Papalote
1 Colonyx COR 4 mi. NE of El Papalote 8:00 PM 78 degrees still light
1 Phyllooohyncus COR 9.5 mi. NE of El Papalote 8:30 PM 70 degrees almost dark
1 Phylloohyncus COR 11 mi. NE of El Papalote 8:40 PM 70 degrees
1 Gecko COR 11 mi. NE of El Papalote 10:05 PM 62 degrees
Quit at Punta Penasco at 10:40 63 degrees
Evening drive 2 hrs 40 min 37 mi

Field noted horned toads
The M'callii taken 10 mi NE of Punta Penasco (next day) was in a dune area of loose drifting sand. Tops of dunes capped with mesquite or creosote. The two platyrkinos taken on the road to Las Chollas Point were in a flat sandy area well covered with burro weed. Here the sand was packed hard - not drifting.
The Umas never seek refuge by burying themselves in the sand. They always go down rodent holes that are plentiful in these dunes.

Went to Sonoyta and took the side road toward Caboca.

135th

Shaws Sonora Trip (Continued)

Left Punta Penasco at 9 A.M., clear, breezy, 74 degrees. Stopped to hunt 12 mi. NE of Punta Penasco. Cats claw, creosote, sand. Got 9 dips, 1 Uta graciosa, 2 C. Wislizenii. Later mating at 11 AM under cats claw on side of a dune. Got 22 Umas. Gravid females contained 3 to 4 eggs; stomach contents composed of both leaves & flowers as well as insects. Plants predominated.

1 Cally DOR 11.5 mi. NE of Punta Penasco Sandy desert - creosote
1 Uma DOR 11 mi. NE of Punta Penasco Sandy desert - creosote
1 C. Wislizenii COR 3 mi. NE of Punta Penasco Sandy desert burrow 2:15 P.M.
Reached Punta Penasco at 2:25 Winsy.
Strated the evening drive from Punta Penasco at 6:55 Clear.
1 Chionactis COR 6.5 mi. NE of Punta Penasco 7:07 73 degrees burro weed, creosoe, sandy desert, breezy
Sundown at 7:37 76 degrees slight breeze
1 Chionactis COR 14 mi. NE of El Papalote 8:07 72 degrees not dark
1 Coleonyx COR 17.5 mi. NE of El Papalote 8:20 71 degrees not dark
1 Coleonyx COR 18 mi. NE of El Papalote 8:35 70 degrees
1 Phyllorhynchus COR 14 mi. NE of El Papalote 8:50 70 degrees

Thursday, June 19, 1947

9:00 a.m.
First Methodist Church
L. M. Klauber, Chairman
JOINT SESSION WITH AMERICAN SOCIETY OF ICHTHYOLOGISTS AND HERPETOLOGISTS
SYMPOSIUM: Speciation in Terrestrial Cold-Blooded Vertebrates

12. The Sedentary Nature of Reptilian Populations and the Rhinocheilus. Charles H. Lowed, Jr., University of California, Los Angeles. 15 minutes
13. Subspecific Differentiation in the Plethodont Genus Ensatna. Robert C. Stebbins, University of California, Berkeley. Illustrated. 45 minutes
14. A Field Sturdy of Homing in the Carolina Toad. Charles M. Bogert, American Museum of Natural History. Illustrated. 15 minutes
15. Behavior as a Factor in Speciation. Robert C. Miller, California Academy of Sciences. 20 minutes.

Robert Glaser worked on Riverside records in the afternoon.
Woodbury and Hardy called at 4 PM with their families, and looked over the plant.

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
